# Tiered API Simulation for Stories

## Context

When writing any story in a design system that involves data

## Pattern

Use a tiered approach: advisory for simple component stories, warning for page stories, strict for prototype-master stories. All tiers prefer API stores over inline mock data.

## Example

```typescript
// Tier 1 - Simple components: inline data OK
export const ButtonVariants: Story = {
  args: { label: 'Click me' }
}

// Tier 2 - Page stories: API store recommended
import { useUserStore } from '@/api/stores/userStore'
export const UsersPage: Story = {
  render: () => {
    const { users } = useUserStore()
    return <UsersPageContent users={users} />
  }
}

// Tier 3 - Prototype master: API store required
import { useTenantStore } from '@/api/stores/tenantStore'
export const Default: Story = {
  render: () => {
    const { tenants, isLoading, createTenant } = useTenantStore()
    return <TenantsPage ... />
  }
}
```

## Why

Simple Button stories don't need API complexity. Page stories benefit from realistic data flow. Prototype masters define contracts - no exceptions.

# Master Story Protocol for Prototype Stories

## Context

When building prototype master stories (*-prototype-master.stories.tsx) that define page compositions

## Pattern

Prototype master stories must use API hooks (useApiStore, useQuery) instead of inline mock data. This ensures the frontend defines the API contract that backend implements.

## Example

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Use API store
import { useTenantStore } from '@/api/stores/tenantStore'

export const Default: Story = {
  render: () => {
    const { tenants, isLoading } = useTenantStore()
    return <TenantsPage tenants={tenants} isLoading={isLoading} />
  }
}

// ❌ FORBIDDEN: Inline mock data
export const Default: Story = {
  args: {
    tenants: [{ id: '1', name: 'Test' }]
  }
}
```

## Why

API hooks define the contract between frontend and backend. When types are defined in stores, backend implements exactly those shapes - no drift between mock data and real API.

# Inline Mock Data in Prototype Stories

## Context

When writing prototype master stories

## Anti-Pattern

Never use inline mock data (const mockData = [...] or args: { data: [...] }) in prototype master stories. This creates drift between what frontend expects and what backend provides.

## Example (Bad)

```typescript
// ❌ ANTI-PATTERN: Inline mock arrays
const mockTenants = [
  { id: '1', name: 'Test Tenant' }
]

export const Default: Story = {
  args: { tenants: mockTenants }
}
```

## Why It's Wrong

Inline mocks are invisible to backend teams, live only in story files, and inevitably drift from real API responses. API stores make the contract explicit and reusable.

## Correct Approach

See: [master-story-protocol](../../patterns/react/master-story-protocol.md)
